Jenny has 8 books in total, and she has 42 pages in each book. So, the total number of pages in all the books together is given by  
\begin{align*}
8 \times 42
\end{align*}
Each page of the 8 books contains 6 stamps. So, all the stamps in the 8 books can be calculated by  
\begin{align*}
6 \times 8 \times 42
\end{align*}
Jenny reorganizes her stamps. Now, each page contains 10 stamps instead of 6, and she has exactly 42 pages in her first 4 books, while her fifth book has 33 pages but she fills up only 33 pages with 10 stamps each and has a remaining page with the rest
So the number of stamps from the first 5 books  
\begin{align*}
10 \times 4 \times 42 + 33 \times 10
\end{align*}
Total number of stamps Jenny has at first can be calculated by subtraction
\begin{align*}
6 \times 8 \times 42 - 10 \times 4 \times 42 - 33 \times 10
\end{align*}
So the remaining number of stamps on the last page would be 12</think> <answer>12</answer>

